re, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europe","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","Of Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"–Aft 1125":"–na 1125","–1125":"–1125","1035–1086":"1035–1086","1060–1129":"1060–1129","0999–1079":"0999–1079","1010–1079":"1010–1079","Aft 1125":"na 1125","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","13 July 1079":"13 juli 1079","1060":"1060","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1016":"1016","1125":"1125","Abt 1079":"circa 1079","1013":"1013","1079":"1079","1035":"1035","Abt 1060":"circa 1060","0999":"0999","Sussex Square, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europa","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","Of Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–Aft 1125":"–after 1125","–1125":"–1125","1035–1086":"1035–1086","1060–1129":"1060–1129","0999–1079":"0999–1079","1010–1079":"1010–1079","Aft 1125":"after 1125","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","13 July 1079":"13 July 1079","1060":"1060","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1016":"1016","1125":"1125","Abt 1079":"about 1079","1013":"1013","1079":"1079","1035":"1035","Abt 1060":"about 1060","0999":"0999","Sussex Square, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Normandie, Europe":"Normandie, Europe","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","Of Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Brittany","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Brittain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brittain","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Anglo-Norman French <i>Bretagne</i>, <i>Bretaign(e)</i> ‘Brittany’. Some of the modern forms are from the Middle English <i>Brytane</i>, <i>Brittan</i> ‘Breton’; compare   Breton  ."]}]},{"name":"and","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Isidor, Myer.","English, German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): metonymic occupational name for a maker of hoops and bands, etc., from Middle English <i>band</i>, <i>bond</i>, Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>bant</i>, German <i>Band</i> ‘hoop, metal band, fetter, shackle’, i.e. something used for tying or binding.","English: variant of   Bond  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bandt","meanings":["German: variant of   Band  ."]},{"name":"Bandstra","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Gerrit, Wouter.","West Frisian: habitational name composed with   Band   4 + the suffix <i>-stra</i> from Old Frisian <i>sittera</i> ‘inhabitant of’."]},{"name":"Banta","meanings":["West Frisian: probably a habitational name for someone from Bant, in the 17th century an island in Friesland, now a village north of Emmeloord in the Noordoostpolder (see   Band   4, compare   Banda   5). This surname is no longer found in the Netherlands.","History: Epke Jacobs Banta arrived in New Netherland in 1659."]},{"name":"Bandel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Zvi, Emanuel, Hyman, Meir.","South German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from a diminutive of   Band  . See also   Bendel  .","German: in some cases, a variant of <b>Pandel</b>, a pet form of the medieval personal name <i>Pantaleon</i> (see   Pantaleo  )."]},{"name":"Bend","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Nottinghamshire): from Middle English <i>bend</i> ‘band, fetter, chain; ribbon, sash, stripe’, for someone who made, wore, or used such items. See also the   Band   1 and compare   Bendy   1."]},{"name":"Bandler","meanings":["German: occupational name for a maker of band (for vessels) or ribbon or lace, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>bandel</i>, a diminutive of <i>bant</i> ‘band’ (see   Band  )."]},{"name":"Bandy","meanings":["English: perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English <i>bandi</i>, <i>bondi</i>, <i>bendi</i>, derivatives of Middle English and Old English <i>band</i>, <i>bond</i>, <i>bend</i> ‘band, ribbon, stripe’ + Middle English <i>-i</i>, reinforced by Old French <i>bendé</i> ‘striped’, with reference perhaps to clothing ornamented with ribbons or stripes, or to the diagonal band of a heraldic device. Compare   Band  .","English: alternatively, perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English <i>bandy</i>, <i>bendy</i> ‘curved stick’, used for someone with bent or crooked legs.","Czech and Slovak: from a derivative of <i>banda</i> ‘(gipsy) band’, apparently a nickname for a bandsman. This surname is found among Gypsies."]},{"name":"Bond","meanings":["English: status name for a peasant farmer or husbandman, Middle English <i>bond(e)</i>, <i>bounde</i>, occasionally <i>bande</i> ‘bondman, customary tenant, serf’ (Old English <i>bonda</i>, <i>bunda</i>, reinforced by Old Norse <i>bóndi</i>). The Old Norse word was also in use as a personal name (Old Norse <i>Bóndi</i>, <i>Bondi</i>, <i>Bundi</i>, <i>Bonde</i>, borrowed as late Old English <i>Bonda</i>), and this has given rise to other English and Scandinavian surnames alongside those originating as status names, such as the Middle English personal name <i>Bonde</i>. The status of the peasant farmer fluctuated considerably during the Middle Ages; moreover, the underlying ancient Germanic word is of disputed origin and meaning. Among ancient Germanic peoples who settled to an agricultural life, the term came to signify a farmer holding lands from, and bound by loyalty to, a lord; from this developed the sense of a free landholder as opposed to a serf. In England after the Norman Conquest the word sank in status and became associated with the notion of bound servitude. The name can also be a variant of   Band  .","Swedish: variant of   Bonde  .","In some cases also an American shortened form of Ukrainian   Bondarenko   and possibly also of some other surname beginning with <i>Bond-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Adeline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["diminutive of <i>Adèle</i> (  see  Adele  ), used occasionally in England from the early 16th century onwards, and now also found in the wider English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705179,"age":5,"year":"1013","julianDay":2091051,"title":"Sweyn Forkbeard","description":"The Danes raided and captured England. Sweyn, King of Danes, was declared King of England on Christmas Day.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweyn_Forkbeard","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Sweyn Forkbeard","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705180,"age":8,"year":"1016","julianDay":2092146,"title":"Canut the Great","description":"As Aethelred, King of England died, his son, Edmund Ironside devised a truce with Danish King Canute. The truce divided the kingdom between the two but Edmund died shortly after and became King of England. Several years later, he also became king of Denmark.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cnut_the_Great","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Cnut the Great","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705182,"age":58,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":78,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":88,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":98,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Adeline of Brittany and Ponthieve was born in Normandie, Europe as the daughter of Count Eudes Ednowain and Agnes Canhiart. She had at least 1 son with Roger de Pitres Sheriff of Gloucester. She died after 1125, in Middlesex, England."},"et":{"–Aft 1125":"–pärast 1125","–1125":"–1125","1035–1086":"1035–1086","1060–1129":"1060–1129","0999–1079":"0999–1079","1010–1079":"1010–1079","Aft 1125":"pärast 1125","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","13 July 1079":"13. juuli 1079","1060":"1060","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1016":"1016","1125":"1125","Abt 1079":"umbes 1079","1013":"1013","1079":"1079","1035":"1035","Abt 1060":"umbes 1060","0999":"0999","Sussex Square, London, Middlesex, Engl